## Sources: What We Cite and What We Don't

**Do not quote or cite WhichSchoolAdvisor, iSchoolAdvisor, or similar review-aggregator sites.** We do not say "WhichSchoolAdvisor notes...", "According to WhichSchoolAdvisor...", or cite their survey percentages (e.g. "42% would recommend"). That reads as if we're summarising someone else's research instead of our own. Remove or rewrite any such references when writing or editing profiles.

**We are happy to refer to the FT (Financial Times) and other serious journalism** when relevant - e.g. "The FT reported on safeguarding concerns in Jan 2026." Name the publication and keep the reference factual and brief.

**Editorial should read as if we're on the ground.** Our authority comes from the impression that we've spoken to people, visited, and formed our own view. In most cases, just say the thing - state the insight directly. Don't pepper every claim with "parents say..." or "families mention..."; that gets repetitive. Use attribution only when it genuinely adds (e.g. grounding a specific or contested claim). We never cite other review sites; we refer to the FT where relevant and otherwise write in our own voice.

**If existing profile copy cites WhichSchoolAdvisor or similar:** revise it when the profile is next updated. Replace with a direct statement in our voice, or sparing attribution where it adds - not a blanket "parents say" in front of everything.

